Experiment 2 — Process Management System Calls

Aim
To study process management system calls in UNIX using C programming.

Algorithm
Start the program.
Use fork() to create child process.
If pid == 0, execute child process.
Else execute parent process.
Parent waits using wait().
Display process IDs.
Stop the program.


System Calls Used
fork() → Create new process
getpid() → Get process ID
getppid() → Get parent process ID
wait() → Parent waits for child
exit() → Terminate process




Program

#include <stdio.h>
#include <unistd.h>
#include <sys/types.h>
#include <sys/wait.h>
#include <stdlib.h>

int main()
{
    pid_t pid;

    pid = fork();

    if(pid < 0)
    {
        printf("Fork Failed\n");
    }
    else if(pid == 0)
    {
        printf("\n--- CHILD PROCESS ---\n");
        printf("Child PID : %d\n", getpid());
        printf("Parent PID: %d\n", getppid());

        printf("Child Process Executing...\n");

        exit(0);
    }
    else
    {
        wait(NULL);

        printf("\n--- PARENT PROCESS ---\n");
        printf("Parent PID : %d\n", getpid());
        printf("Child PID  : %d\n", pid);

        printf("Parent Process Executing...\n");
    }

    return 0;
}




